{{ 'kt-section-customer-forms.css' | asset_url | stylesheet_tag }}
{{ 'kt-section-customer-account.css' | asset_url | stylesheet_tag }}

<section class="kt-customer kt-customer--wide" data-section-id="{{ section.id }}" data-section-type="main-order">
  <div class="kt-customer__container kt-customer__container--wide">
    <a href="{{ routes.account_url }}" class="kt-order__back">
      &larr; {{ 'kt.customer.order.back_to_account' | t }}
    </a>

    {%- comment -%}
      Account sidebar + content layout. Previously the order page
      rendered the title + body directly inside the wide container
      with only a single "← Back to account" link as navigation. A
      customer deep-linking to /account/orders/:id (bookmark, email
      receipt link) and hitting refresh would lose the account
      shell entirely — no path to Addresses, no Logout. Wrapping in
      the shared `.kt-account__layout` + rendering the same sidebar
      restores the shell on every account URL. `current: 'orders'`
      marks the Details link active because this order detail view
      is conceptually reached from the Details landing.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- assign order_date_formatted = order.created_at | date: format: 'date' -%}
    <div class="kt-account__layout">
      {%- render 'account-nav', current: 'orders' -%}
      <div class="kt-account__content">
        <header class="kt-account__header kt-order__title-block">
          <h1 class="kt-customer__title kt-order__title-heading">
            {{ 'kt.customer.order.title' | t: name: order.name }}
          </h1>
          <p class="kt-account__greeting">
            {{ 'kt.customer.order.date_html' | t: date: order_date_formatted }}
          </p>
        </header>

    {%- comment -%}
      Cancelled-order banner. `order.cancelled_at` is set when the
      merchant (or customer-support agent) cancels the order.
      `cancel_reason_label` is localised by Shopify. Without this
      banner the only visual cue a cancelled order gives is the
      financial_status pill reading "Refunded" — not enough to
      distinguish "shipped and refunded" from "cancelled before
      fulfillment". Surfacing the cancellation date + reason here
      prevents the "why hasn't my order shipped" support ticket.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- if order.cancelled_at != blank -%}
      {%- assign cancelled_date = order.cancelled_at | date: format: 'date' -%}
      <div class="kt-order__cancelled" role="note">
        <p class="kt-order__cancelled-heading">
          {{ 'kt.customer.order.cancelled_heading' | t: date: cancelled_date }}
        </p>
        {%- if order.cancel_reason_label != blank -%}
          <p class="kt-order__cancelled-reason">
            {{ 'kt.customer.order.cancelled_reason' | t: reason: order.cancel_reason_label }}
          </p>
        {%- endif -%}
      </div>
    {%- endif -%}

    <div class="kt-order__meta" role="group" aria-label="{{ 'kt.customer.order.title' | t: name: order.name }}">
      <div class="kt-order__meta-item">
        <span class="kt-order__meta-label">{{ 'kt.customer.order.payment_status' | t }}</span>
        <span class="kt-order__meta-value">
          <span class="kt-account__pill kt-account__pill--{{ order.financial_status }}">
            {{ order.financial_status_label }}
          </span>
        </span>
      </div>
      <div class="kt-order__meta-item">
        <span class="kt-order__meta-label">{{ 'kt.customer.order.fulfillment_status' | t }}</span>
        <span class="kt-order__meta-value">
          <span class="kt-account__pill kt-account__pill--{{ order.fulfillment_status | default: 'unfulfilled' }}">
            {{ order.fulfillment_status_label }}
          </span>
        </span>
      </div>
    </div>

    {%- comment -%}
      Shipment tracking links. `order.fulfillments` is populated once
      the order is partially/fully fulfilled; each fulfillment carries
      a carrier + tracking number + tracking URL. Without this block
      the customer has no way to track their package from the order
      page — they have to dig into the shipping-confirmation email.
      Gate on fulfillments.size so pending orders render nothing
      extra.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- comment -%}
      Pending-fulfillment note. When an order has been placed but no
      fulfillment has started yet (common first 1-6 hours post-order),
      the tracking block below renders nothing, which looked to
      customers like tracking info was missing rather than pending.
      This note fills the gap with a reassuring "we'll update you"
      copy, suppressed once a fulfillment exists or the order is
      cancelled (cancellation note above already explains THAT state).
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- if order.fulfillments.size == 0 and order.cancelled_at == blank -%}
      <div class="kt-order__pending" role="note">
        <p class="kt-order__pending-text">
          {{ 'kt.customer.order.pending_fulfillment' | t | default: 'Your order is being prepared. Tracking details will appear here once it ships.' }}
        </p>
      </div>
    {%- endif -%}

    {%- if order.fulfillments.size > 0 -%}
      <div class="kt-order__tracking" aria-label="{{ 'kt.customer.order.tracking_heading' | t }}">
        <h2 class="kt-order__tracking-heading">{{ 'kt.customer.order.tracking_heading' | t }}</h2>
        <ul class="kt-order__tracking-list" role="list">
          {%- for fulfillment in order.fulfillments -%}
            <li class="kt-order__tracking-item">
              {%- if fulfillment.tracking_company != blank -%}
                <span class="kt-order__tracking-carrier">{{ fulfillment.tracking_company }}</span>
              {%- endif -%}
              {%- if fulfillment.tracking_url != blank -%}
                <a href="{{ fulfillment.tracking_url | escape }}" class="kt-order__tracking-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
                  {%- if fulfillment.tracking_number != blank -%}
                    {{ 'kt.customer.order.track_package_with_number' | t: number: fulfillment.tracking_number }}
                  {%- else -%}
                    {{ 'kt.customer.order.track_package' | t }}
                  {%- endif -%}
                </a>
              {%- elsif fulfillment.tracking_number != blank -%}
                <span class="kt-order__tracking-number">{{ fulfillment.tracking_number }}</span>
              {%- endif -%}
            </li>
          {%- endfor -%}
        </ul>
      </div>
    {%- endif -%}

    <div class="kt-order__layout">
      {%- comment -%} Line items {%- endcomment -%}
      <div class="kt-order__items" role="table" aria-label="{{ 'kt.customer.order.product' | t }}">
        {%- for line_item in order.line_items -%}
          <div class="kt-order__item" role="row">
            {%- if line_item.image -%}
              {{ line_item.image | image_url: width: 160 | image_tag:
                loading: 'lazy',
                width: 80,
                height: 80,
                class: 'kt-order__item-image',
                alt: line_item.image.alt | default: line_item.title
              }}
            {%- else -%}
              {%- comment -%}
                Shopify placeholder SVG keeps the 80×80 slot visually
                balanced when a line item has no product image
                (imported orders, deleted products, digital goods).
                An empty <div> left a blank square that looked like a
                broken asset and shifted row height inconsistently
                between items — Theme Store's empty-state rule
                requires a visible fallback on every image slot.
              {%- endcomment -%}
              {{ 'product-1' | placeholder_svg_tag: 'kt-order__item-image kt-order__item-image--placeholder' }}
            {%- endif -%}

            <div>
              <p class="kt-order__item-title">
                {%- if line_item.url != blank -%}
                  <a href="{{ line_item.url }}">{{ line_item.product.title | default: line_item.title }}</a>
                {%- else -%}
                  {{ line_item.product.title | default: line_item.title }}
                {%- endif -%}
              </p>
              {%- unless line_item.product.has_only_default_variant -%}
                <p class="kt-order__item-variant">{{ line_item.variant.title }}</p>
              {%- endunless -%}
              {%- if line_item.sku != blank -%}
                <p class="kt-order__item-sku">{{ 'kt.customer.order.sku' | t: sku: line_item.sku }}</p>
              {%- endif -%}
              <p class="kt-order__item-qty">{{ 'kt.customer.order.qty' | t: qty: line_item.quantity }}</p>

              {%- comment -%}
                Unit price disclosure (EU groceries/wellness regulation)
                + selling plan name (subscription compliance) — Theme
                Store Section 7 customer-page requirements.
              {%- endcomment -%}
              {%- if line_item.variant.unit_price_measurement -%}
                <p class="kt-order__item-unit-price">
                  {{- line_item.variant.unit_price | money -}}
                  <span aria-hidden="true">/</span>
                  {%- if line_item.variant.unit_price_measurement.reference_value != 1 -%}
                    {{- line_item.variant.unit_price_measurement.reference_value -}}
                  {%- endif -%}
                  {{- line_item.variant.unit_price_measurement.reference_unit -}}
                </p>
              {%- endif -%}
              {%- if line_item.selling_plan_allocation -%}
                <p class="kt-order__item-plan">{{ line_item.selling_plan_allocation.selling_plan.name | escape }}</p>
              {%- endif -%}

              {%- comment -%}
                Line item properties — customer-supplied customization
                fields captured at cart time (engraving copy, gift
                message, custom configuration JSON, etc.). The cart
                page and cart drawer both display these so the
                customer can verify their input before checkout, but
                the order receipt was missing them — meaning a
                customer who ordered a personalized engraving had no
                way to confirm the engraving copy from their order
                history. Theme Store reviewers test this surface as
                part of the customer-account critical path.

                `_`-prefixed property keys are private (used by apps
                to attach metadata) and should be skipped. File
                upload properties expose `last` as the relative URL,
                not a string — render as a download link.
              {%- endcomment -%}
              {%- assign visible_properties = false -%}
              {%- for property in line_item.properties -%}
                {%- assign property_first_char = property.first | slice: 0 -%}
                {%- if property.last != blank and property_first_char != '_' -%}
                  {%- assign visible_properties = true -%}
                  {%- break -%}
                {%- endif -%}
              {%- endfor -%}
              {%- if visible_properties -%}
                <ul class="kt-order__item-properties" role="list">
                  {%- for property in line_item.properties -%}
                    {%- assign first_char = property.first | slice: 0 -%}
                    {%- if property.last == blank or first_char == '_' -%}{% continue %}{%- endif -%}
                    <li class="kt-order__item-property">
                      <span class="kt-order__item-property-name">{{ property.first }}:</span>
                      {%- if property.last contains '/uploads/' -%}
                        <a href="{{ property.last | escape }}" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
                          {{ property.last | split: '/' | last }}
                        </a>
                      {%- else -%}
                        <span class="kt-order__item-property-value">{{ property.last }}</span>
                      {%- endif -%}
                    </li>
                  {%- endfor -%}
                </ul>
              {%- endif -%}

              {%- comment -%}
                Per-line fulfillment status. When an order ships in
                waves — 2 of 3 items today, the third in 4 days —
                `order.fulfillment_status` only reports the aggregate
                ("partial") and the customer can't tell which item
                belongs to which shipment. `line_item.fulfillment`
                resolves to the specific fulfillment covering this
                line; if it's nil, the line is still unfulfilled.
              {%- endcomment -%}
              {%- if line_item.fulfillment -%}
                <p class="kt-order__item-fulfillment kt-order__item-fulfillment--shipped">
                  {%- assign line_fulfilled_date = line_item.fulfillment.created_at | date: format: 'date' -%}
                  {{ 'kt.customer.order.line_fulfilled_on' | t: date: line_fulfilled_date }}
                </p>
              {%- elsif line_item.successfully_fulfilled_quantity > 0 and line_item.successfully_fulfilled_quantity < line_item.quantity -%}
                <p class="kt-order__item-fulfillment kt-order__item-fulfillment--partial">
                  {{ 'kt.customer.order.line_partial' | t: shipped: line_item.successfully_fulfilled_quantity, total: line_item.quantity }}
                </p>
              {%- endif -%}
            </div>

            <div class="kt-order__item-price">
              {{ line_item.final_line_price | money }}
            </div>
          </div>
        {%- endfor -%}
      </div>

      {%- comment -%} Totals {%- endcomment -%}
      <aside class="kt-order__totals" aria-label="{{ 'kt.customer.order.total' | t }}">
        <div class="kt-order__totals-row">
          <span>{{ 'kt.customer.order.subtotal' | t }}</span>
          <span>{{ order.line_items_subtotal_price | money }}</span>
        </div>

        {%- comment -%}
          Discount breakdown. Previously surfaced only an aggregate
          "Discount: -$X" line; customers filing disputes or cross-
          checking promotional emails had no way to see which codes
          actually applied. `order.cart_level_discount_applications`
          lists each applied code with its localised title and saved
          amount. Fall back to the aggregate row when no code-level
          attributions exist (e.g., an automatic discount that the
          API doesn't attribute to an individual code).
        {%- endcomment -%}
        {%- if order.cart_level_discount_applications.size > 0 -%}
          {%- for discount in order.cart_level_discount_applications -%}
            <div class="kt-order__totals-row kt-order__totals-row--discount">
              <span>{{ 'kt.customer.order.discount' | t }} ({{ discount.title }})</span>
              <span>-{{ discount.total_allocated_amount | money }}</span>
            </div>
          {%- endfor -%}
        {%- elsif order.total_discounts > 0 -%}
          <div class="kt-order__totals-row">
            <span>{{ 'kt.customer.order.discount' | t }}</span>
            <span>-{{ order.total_discounts | money }}</span>
          </div>
        {%- endif -%}

        {%- for shipping_method in order.shipping_methods -%}
          <div class="kt-order__totals-row">
            <span>{{ 'kt.customer.order.shipping' | t }}{% if shipping_method.title %} ({{ shipping_method.title }}){% endif %}</span>
            <span>{{ shipping_method.price | money }}</span>
          </div>
        {%- endfor -%}

        {%- for tax_line in order.tax_lines -%}
          <div class="kt-order__totals-row">
            <span>{{ 'kt.customer.order.tax' | t }}{% if tax_line.title %} ({{ tax_line.title }}){% endif %}</span>
            <span>{{ tax_line.price | money }}</span>
          </div>
        {%- endfor -%}

        <div class="kt-order__totals-row kt-order__totals-row--grand">
          <span>{{ 'kt.customer.order.total' | t }}</span>
          <span>{{ order.total_price | money_with_currency }}</span>
        </div>

        {%- comment -%}
          Refund summary — when an order has been partially or fully
          refunded, customers need to see (a) what was refunded and
          (b) what they actually paid net. Without these rows the
          grand-total line above overstates the customer's payment
          after any refund event. order.total_refunded sums every
          refund_line_item.subtotal + refund.transactions adjustments;
          order.net_payment is the true paid amount.
        {%- endcomment -%}
        {%- if order.total_refunded_set.shop_money.amount > 0 -%}
          <div class="kt-order__totals-row kt-order__totals-row--refund">
            <span>{{ 'kt.customer.order.refunded' | t | default: 'Refunded' }}</span>
            <span>– {{ order.total_refunded_set | money_with_currency }}</span>
          </div>
          <div class="kt-order__totals-row kt-order__totals-row--net">
            <span>{{ 'kt.customer.order.net_payment' | t | default: 'Net paid' }}</span>
            <span>{{ order.net_payment_set | money_with_currency }}</span>
          </div>
        {%- endif -%}
      </aside>
    </div>

    {%- comment -%} Addresses {%- endcomment -%}
    <div class="kt-order__addresses">
      {%- if order.shipping_address -%}
        <div class="kt-order__address-card">
          <h2 class="kt-order__address-title">{{ 'kt.customer.order.shipping_address' | t }}</h2>
          <address class="kt-order__address-body">{{ order.shipping_address | format_address }}</address>
        </div>
      {%- endif -%}

      {%- if order.billing_address -%}
        <div class="kt-order__address-card">
          <h2 class="kt-order__address-title">{{ 'kt.customer.order.billing_address' | t }}</h2>
          <address class="kt-order__address-body">{{ order.billing_address | format_address }}</address>
        </div>
      {%- endif -%}
    </div>

    {%- comment -%}
      Customer-facing order note. The `cart.note` the customer wrote
      on checkout lands on `order.note`. Before this block the note
      was invisible on the account order page — a known support-ticket
      driver ("Did you see my delivery instructions?"). Rendered
      read-only; customers edit via contacting support, not here.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- if order.note != blank -%}
      <div class="kt-order__note">
        <h2 class="kt-order__note-title">{{ 'kt.customer.order.note_heading' | t | default: 'Order note' }}</h2>
        <p class="kt-order__note-body">{{ order.note | escape | newline_to_br }}</p>
      </div>
    {%- endif -%}

    {%- comment -%}
      Custom cart attributes carried from checkout into the order —
      Shopify surfaces them as `order.attributes` (hash of
      merchant-defined OR B2B buyer-populated key/value pairs).
      Common uses:
        - B2B purchase-order number (`attributes['PO Number']`)
        - B2B cost centre / project code
        - Gift-recipient shipping scheduling date ("Deliver on")
        - Custom engraving text on multi-line orders
      Without this block, a B2B buyer reviewing their order page
      sees NO reference to their PO number, which is the #1
      merchant-service complaint on B2B stores. Rendered as a
      definition list so assistive tech announces key: value pairs
      correctly. Both key + value escaped (attribute name/value
      are user-typed).
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- if order.attributes != blank and order.attributes.size > 0 -%}
      <div class="kt-order__attributes">
        <h2 class="kt-order__attributes-title">{{ 'kt.customer.order.attributes_heading' | t | default: 'Order details' }}</h2>
        <dl class="kt-order__attributes-list">
          {%- for attribute in order.attributes -%}
            {%- assign attr_key = attribute.first | strip -%}
            {%- assign attr_first_char = attr_key | slice: 0, 1 -%}
            {%- unless attr_key == blank or attr_first_char == '_' -%}
              <dt class="kt-order__attributes-key">{{ attr_key | escape }}</dt>
              <dd class="kt-order__attributes-value">{{ attribute.last | escape }}</dd>
            {%- endunless -%}
          {%- endfor -%}
        </dl>
      </div>
    {%- endif -%}
      </div>{%- comment -%} /.kt-account__content {%- endcomment -%}
    </div>{%- comment -%} /.kt-account__layout {%- endcomment -%}
  </div>
</section>

{% schema %}
{
  "name": "t:sections.main-order.name",
  "tag": "div",
  "class": "section",
  "enabled_on": {
    "templates": ["customers/order"]
  }
}
{% endschema %}
